{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS-1 PLAN REVIEW — [G6] Approach soundness, anti-patterns & alternative-selection — VERDICT: PASS (no findings).\n\nI assessed the epic's CHOSEN APPROACH against all four G6 dimensions, treating the compiled state (body + the authoritative re-triage/scope comments) as one plan, and grounding mechanism reasoning in the live engine code (src/rebar/llm/workflow/*).\n\n(1) MECHANISM CORRECTNESS — sound. This epic's load-bearing mechanism is a PROCESS (capture scope → dedicated brainstorm does the deep design BEFORE implementation → decompose into workstreams), and the mechanism demonstrably executed correctly: the brainstorm produced a grounded architecture decision (comment, session log ad3f), the engine BUILD was correctly spun out into its own epic (e6d9) with this epic set depends_on it, and the visual/validate/migrate workstreams were re-triaged against shipped code. The one open mechanism question the body raises — WS-MIGRATE's CAVEAT that \"the engine is a thin LINEAR executor (graphlib) … the gate's dynamic fan-out … may exceed the DSL; resolve whether the DSL gains map/fan-out steps\" — is explicitly deferred to the brainstorm AND is already resolved in the shipped code: src/rebar/llm/workflow/map_fanout.py ships bounded-concurrent map fan-out (the SOLE, recorded Burr-tripwire relaxation; order-independent, iteration-keyed idempotency markers, lock-serialized commits), so the fan-out concern does not break the migration approach. The RE-TRIAGE comments correctly reconcile the now-stale seed body against this (e6d9 closed; gates/plan-review.yaml + gates/completion-verification.yaml exist), so the plan's own text resolves the apparent staleness rather than leaving a live mechanism defect. No hidden ordering/atomicity/TOCTOU hazard found.\n\n(2) FITNESS-FOR-PURPOSE — solves the NAMED problem (a remediation epic capturing the four real gaps: no usage doc, fragmented LLM substrate, silently-deferred bidirectional visual editing, no production-prompt home) rather than a proxy. The narrowed remaining scope (WS-DOC docs/workflow-engine.md; WS-EVAL-EXISTING eval coverage for the migrated reviewers) is the genuine residual, and the latest scope comment grounds it concretely (the WS-EVAL Phase-2 \"inert deterministic-scorer registry / agentic-reviewers-not-inline-feedable\" findings are real code facts, correctly folded in).\n\n(3) APPROACH SELECTION — WS-VALIDATE is itself a built-in alternatives evaluation, and the architecture-decision comment documents a thorough structural survey (DBOS/Restate/SpiffWorkflow-BPMN/Temporal/Prefect/Dagster/LangGraph/n8n/Node-RED/Argo) with the engine kept-and-rebuilt on a defensible constraint (event-sourced run-state on a git-backed event log that no off-the-shelf durable-execution library can defer to). I generated two structurally-different alternatives — (a) adopt an off-the-shelf engine (SpiffWorkflow/Temporal) instead of the homegrown interpreter, and (b) keep LLM logic bespoke and skip the engine-unification — and both are defensibly INFERIOR on the named constraints (off-the-shelf engines own their persistence and can't sit on the git event log; bespoke duplication is the exact fragmentation the epic exists to remove). No clearly-superior missed alternative; alternatives discarded, not written into the plan (anti-priming respected). The \"don't reinvent — adopt an established visual-editing ecosystem\" concern further shows the anti-NIH discipline applied to itself (resolved as ephemeral bpmn-js projection in e6d9).\n\n(4) POSITIVE RATIONALE — present and abundant: build-not-adopt is justified by the event-sourced/git-text axle; the provider-agnostic runtime is justified by the cross-provider hard requirement + Langfuse going OTel-native; visual editing as an ephemeral non-persisted projection is justified by the n8n/Windmill dual-store reconciliation cautionary tale. No rejected-alternatives section is forced into the implementer-facing plan (correct anti-priming).\n\nANTI-FP honored: this is a genuine design/scoping epic with real structural choices (engine build vs adopt; visual format; substrate unification), so alternative-generation was warranted; correctness reasoning was grounded in the actual engine code (map_fanout.py, gates/*.yaml, the depends_on→e6d9 split), not manufactured.\n\naffirmations: G6 — mechanism correctness (process mechanism executed correctly; the one open DSL-fanout question is both brainstorm-deferred and already resolved in shipped map_fanout.py); fitness-for-purpose (captures the four real gaps; residual scope grounded in code); approach selection defensible vs reviewer-generated alternatives (engine build-not-adopt + ephemeral visual projection, no clearly-superior missed option); positive rationale stated for every major chosen approach."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782578701976011001,"uuid":"c95701b9-6fc4-4458-8434-e5f7775c7bdb"}